Year = {2023},
Volume = {211},
Pages = {24-36},
Month = {NOV 1},
Abstract = {Localization techniques play a fundamental role in various applications
   like in the development of smart cities, making the improvement of such
   technologies indispensable. In this context, radio frequency (RF)
   fingerprinting (FP)-based localization methods are attractive due to
   their lower implementation cost, lower energy consumption, and better
   performance in non-line-of-sight conditions compared to GPS. With this
   in mind, we propose an RF FP-based localization method using an
   irregular grid map generation strategy. The grid map segmentation
   procedure is based on the assumption that the RF measurements collected
   in a region carry information on how users are often spatially
   distributed. The algorithms employed in the irregular grid map
   generation are the farthest-first traversal and low-discrepancy
   R-sequence. Different irregular grid map generators are compared with
   each other and with the regular grid map. We evaluate the generators in
   two different scenarios: with measurements obtained through simulation
   with ns-3 and via a driving-test procedure in an urban area. Numerical
   results indicate that our proposed irregular generator presents a lower
   localization error in both scenarios and is the only one capable of
   meeting one of the accuracy requirements stated by the Federal
   Communications Commission that demands a localization error of up to 50
   m in 80\% of the emergency calls.},
