Title = {A Cybertwin-Assisted Pervasive Computing Framework for Edge-Blurred
   Image Segmentation Using Evolutionary Neural Computing},
Journal = {HUMAN-CENTRIC COMPUTING AND INFORMATION SCIENCES},
Year = {2024},
Volume = {14},
Month = {DEC 15},
Abstract = {This work takes aim at how challenging image segmentation tasks where
   edges are blurred still are. As a consequence, evolutionary neural
   computing (ENC) is introduced to develop an enhanced segmentation model
   for such scenes. This calls for strong computing power and sufficient
   bearing capacity. In future smart cities, fortunately,
   cybertwin-assisted pervasive computing has been a more practical way to
   facilitate deploying various intelligent perception tasks. Thus, this
   paper uses a cybertwin-assisted pervasive computing framework for edge-
   blurred image segmentation using ENC. The technical methodology
   comprises two main parts, namely the backbone network and parameter
   evolution. On the one hand, the grayscale segmentation is first
   transferred as a pixel-level binary classification task. The main
   network structure of the proposal is a convolution neural network model
   composed of several computing layers and one parameter updating layer.
   Alternatively, the adaptive genetic algorithm is introduced to
   re-optimize parameters during each round. Two groups of real-world
   images are collected to construct experimental scenarios for carrying
   out two aspects of assessment work. For one thing, the training process
   of the proposed model is visualized to inspect its training effect. For
   another, the proposed model is compared with three baseline methods to
   prove its performance superiority. In conclusion, the introduction of
   evolutionary computing can produce improvements of more than 10
   percentage points.},
